hapter plus an appendix provide a set of take-home points on how readers can myth-bust on their own. Accessible, compelling, and original, this book is a rich and nuanced account of how nature, culture, experience, and choice interact to influence human behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBehavior evolution. 0aHuman behavior. 0aHuman evolution. 0aPhysical anthropology. 0aSocial evolution. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Physical.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  abiological anthropology.  aethnography.  aevolution of mankind.  aevolution.  ahuman aggression.  ahuman and race.  ahuman behavior.  ahuman biology.  ahuman culture.  ahuman desires.  ahuman evolution.  ahuman genetics.  ahuman misconceptions.  ahuman myths.  ahuman nature.  ahuman origins.  ahuman psychology.  ahuman sciences.  ahumans and race.  ahumans and sex.  amale vs female.  amonogamous relationship.  amonogamy and polygamy.  anatural science.  anature vs nuture.  aphysical anthropology.  asocial psychology.  astory of mankind.  astudy of humans.0 cprintz978052026971240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095167940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951679423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520951679/original  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY